  "title": "Binary Tree Level Order Traversal",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "tags": [
    "Tree",
    "Breadth-First Search",
    "Binary Tree"
  ],
  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Binary Tree Level Order Traversal\n\nReturn the node values grouped by depth from top to bottom and left to right within each level.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: root = [3,9,20,null,null,15,7]\nOutput: [[3],[9,20],[15,7]]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: root = [1]\nOutput: [[1]]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: root = []\nOutput: []\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- The judge provides a `TreeNode` class with `val`, `left`, and `right` fields.\n- Trees are shown in level-order form with `null` for missing children.\n- Node counts are sized for local offline execution.",
  "editorial": "Breadth-first search naturally processes the tree one level at a time. Capture the queue size before each level.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nfrom collections import deque\n\nclass Solution:\n    def levelOrder(self, root):\n        if not root:\n            return []\n        out = []\n        queue = deque([root])\n        while queue:\n            level = []\n            for _ in range(len(queue)):\n                node = queue.popleft()\n                level.append(node.val)\n                if node.left:\n                    queue.append(node.left)\n                if node.right:\n                    queue.append(node.right)\n            out.append(level)\n        return out\n```",
  "hints": [
    "A queue gives nodes in depth order.",
    "The current queue length marks the boundary of a level."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def levelOrder(self, root):\n        pass\n"
  },
  "entrypoint": {
    "class_name": "Solution",
    "method_name": "levelOrder"
  },
  "checker": {
    "type": "exact"
  },
  "time_limit_ms": 2000,
  "memory_limit_mb": 256,
